# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Cursor Project Rules  (machine-friendly)
# Every directive uses the form  “ALWAYS …”  for easy parsing.
# Blocks are separated by   ## SECTION   lines.
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## 🚀 PERFORMANCE & TODO DISCIPLINE (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS call `_print_todo_snapshot()` at the very start of `QuarkDriver.process_prompt`.
ALWAYS update task status via `todo_write` on every success or failure path.
ALWAYS call `update_memory` when a task is mentioned only in chat.
ALWAYS read large files with `offset/limit` or `read_text_cached`.
ALWAYS batch independent edits/searches with `multi_tool_use.parallel`.
ALWAYS pass non-interactive flags (`--quiet`, `--yes`) to long-running commands.
ALWAYS verify wall-clock latency (driver prints timing table) and keep average ≤ 2 s.
ALWAYS keep roadmap YAMLs (`tasks_high.yaml`, `tasks_medium.yaml`, `tasks_low.yaml`) in sync with the master roadmap; any update to one side MUST immediately propagate to the other via the task_loader.
ALWAYS refrain from marking a task complete until it has been validated as complete (tests pass or user approval).
ALWAYS break tasks into small, numbered steps and reference the total count (e.g., "step 2 of 8") in conversational output *important* Always avoid gaps and monitor for overconfidence.
ALWAYS execute code automatically in the foreground; background jobs are disallowed except the user explicitly requests otherwise.
ALWAYS prompt for explicit approval before any file deletion or move operation.

## 🗺️ MARKDOWN & CROSS-LINK AWARENESS (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS at session start run `glob_file_search("**/*.md")` to collect Markdown paths.
ALWAYS batch-read first 120 lines of each Markdown file in parallel.
ALWAYS read `README.md` in any directory before reading source files there.
ALWAYS embed relative links to relevant docs when generating/updating Markdown.
ALWAYS verify that each embedded link resolves; warn if not.

## 🛑 DOCUMENTATION-FIRST GUARD (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS complete the Markdown discovery phase before any code-editing tool call.
ALWAYS abort code edits and prompt the user if any README/Markdown fails to load.
ALWAYS track `markdown_discovery_complete = True/False` and enforce the guard.

## 🚫 REDUNDANT-CODE GUARD (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS, before creating a new file or adding >15 lines:
ALWAYS run `codebase_search` (“Where is X functionality already implemented?”).
ALWAYS run `grep` for matching symbols.
ALWAYS reuse or extend existing code if ≥60 % of behaviour matches.
ALWAYS document why new code is needed when no match exists.
ALWAYS raise an internal assertion if Steps 1–4 are skipped.

## 🧱 ARCHITECTURE & QUALITY (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS write statically-typed Python and run `mypy --strict`.
ALWAYS satisfy Ruff/flake8 + black + isort with no warnings.
ALWAYS include Google/NumPy docstrings for every public symbol.
ALWAYS validate all inputs; never log secrets; follow least privilege.
ALWAYS add/update unit tests with ≥2 edge cases.
ALWAYS keep coverage ≥90 % (`pytest --cov`).
ALWAYS benchmark hot paths when algorithmic complexity changes.
ALWAYS update docs and embed relative links when behaviour changes.
ALWAYS make atomic commits with Conventional Commit messages.
ALWAYS keep PRs <400 LOC; stack larger changes.
ALWAYS run lint → type-check → tests → coverage → build in CI.
ALWAYS fail CI on any warning; publish coverage & benchmark deltas.
ALWAYS write advanced tests that exercise edge cases, invalid input, performance limits, and unexpected behaviour scenarios.

## 🛰️ / 💾 MODEL RETRIEVAL & LOADING (GLOBAL)
ALWAYS prefer remote inference (HF endpoints / TGI) when local storage isn’t required.
ALWAYS respect `HF_ENDPOINT` / `HF_TOKEN` / proxy variables.
ALWAYS fall back to progressive shard download (`snapshot_download(resume_download=True)`).
ALWAYS stream datasets with `datasets.load_dataset(..., streaming=True)`.
ALWAYS load local weights with `device_map="auto"` and `torch_dtype=float16` if supported.
ALWAYS memory-map weights (`low_cpu_mem_usage=True`).
ALWAYS abort load if estimated footprint >55 GB on M2 Max.
ALWAYS log model name, device_map, dtype, peak RAM/VRAM usage.
ALWAYS avoid duplicate weight files inside repo; reference cache or `data/models/`.

## 🧍‍♂️ MODE-SPECIFIC BEHAVIOURS
### CHAT / PLAN MODE
ALWAYS ask scaffold questions when prompt is ambiguous.
ALWAYS, when the user asks "are you certain", re-run validation checks (duplicate-code search, lint, tests) and propose at least one alternative solution not previously presented.
ALWAYS treat the keyword "evolve" as an instruction to proceed with Quark’s recommendations provided they are backed by current scientific literature, and ensure Quark’s overarching goal to evolve and advance science remains active.
### EDIT / REFACTOR MODE
ALWAYS minimise diff and preserve behaviour unless asked.
### GENERATE CODE MODE
ALWAYS implement MVP first; add TODOs for stretch goals.
### FIX / DEBUG MODE
ALWAYS reproduce the bug with a minimal case and state root cause.
ALWAYS provide both fix **and** regression test.
ALWAYS debug in foreground until resolved; pause only for needed info.
ALWAYS list exact paths for delete/move ops and wait for user approval.
### EXPLAIN MODE
ALWAYS summarise the overall flow at a high level *only after* tasks/goals are complete, and ensure that the underlying tasks and recommendations remain highly technical and specific (the user does not need to read every task detail, only the final summary).
### COMMIT MESSAGE MODE
ALWAYS use Conventional Commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`…).
### TEST MODE
ALWAYS cover core paths + ≥2 edge cases; avoid brittle assertions.
ALWAYS execute tests with `pytest -q --durations=10` and fix any slow (>1 s) test.
ALWAYS execute every test the agent creates and resolve any errors before proceeding.
ALWAYS create integration tests for every new integration; unit + performance tests for ML modules.
### DOCS / README MODE
ALWAYS include overview, setup, usage, configuration, examples, troubleshooting.

## 🧠 QUARK PROJECT SPECIFIC RULES
ALWAYS respect directory schema:
  • `brain/`  – neural core + ML sub-systems (`brain/ml/`)
  • `data_knowledge/` – data & models
  • `tests/` – test suites & benchmarks
  • `tools_utilities/` – helper scripts
  • `management/` – configs & project management (`management/rules/`)
  • `state/` – runtime agent state
  • `docs/` – all documentation
  • `repo_indexes/` – generated manifests
ALWAYS note that historical dirs (`brain_architecture/`, `integration/`) no longer exist; do NOT recreate.
ALWAYS follow file-type routing:
  • Scripts → `tools_utilities/scripts/`
  • Configs → `management/configurations/project/`
  • Notebooks → `docs/notebooks/`
  • Documentation → `docs/`
  • Results → `tests/results_outputs/`
  • Models → `data/models/`
  • Experiments → `tests/results_outputs/experiments/`
ALWAYS obey TOP-LEVEL PLACEMENT GUARD:
  • Never create files at repo root unless core entry-points (`README.md`, `pyproject.toml`, `QUARK_STATE_SYSTEM.py`).
ALWAYS include tests with new code; maintain directory structure; preserve backups.

## 📂 MANAGEMENT / RULES LOADER
ALWAYS read every file in `management/rules/` and load its contents into memory **before** responding to the first user prompt in a session.

## 🆘 GOOD FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS (META)
ALWAYS ask target-ed, bundled questions when any of the Universal Checklist items is missing (goal, scope, tech stack, etc.).
ALWAYS apply every rule in this file to the **current codebase as well as all future changes**; if an existing file violates a rule, refactor or document an exception before proceeding.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Simulation Entry Points
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALWAYS treat `brain/architecture/brain_simulator.py` and `embodied_brain_simulation.py` as the PRIMARY entry points for Quark brain simulations.
ALWAYS ensure all **new and existing** brain-related or biologically-informed ML modules integrate with these simulators, or include a written rationale explaining why integration is not applicable.
ALWAYS design such integrations around executive-function pathways (prefrontal cortex, decision layers, etc.) when applicable.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Biological Compliance – Alphagenome Integration (must remain last in block)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALWAYS enforce **Alphagenome Criteria** for any code that interfaces with
 biological simulation, genetic algorithms, or brain-module ML components.

ALWAYS load the following reference implementations into memory at session
 start so the agent can replicate their coding patterns and validation logic:
  • `brain/modules/alphagenome_integration/biological_simulator.py`
  • `brain/modules/alphagenome_integration/dna_controller.py`
  • `brain/modules/alphagenome_integration/genome_analyzer.py`
  • `brain/modules/alphagenome_integration/cell_constructor.py`

ALWAYS, before modifying or extending biological code, verify compliance with
 Alphagenome domain rules (naming conventions, unit balances, biological
 constraints) and cite the specific rule in commit messages.

ALWAYS include edge-case biological tests (e.g., malformed genome strings,
 boundary diffusion parameters) when touching these modules.

ALWAYS load supporting documentation `docs/alphagenome_integration_readme.md` at
 session start so design decisions remain aligned with the written spec.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Safety & Emergency Compliance (must follow Alphagenome block)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALWAYS pre-load the following safety-critical modules and documents at session
 start to ensure all code changes respect shutdown / guardrail logic:
  • `management/emergency/emergency_control.py`
  • `management/emergency/emergency_shutdown_system.py`
  • `brain/architecture/safety/safety_guardian.py`
  • `docs/safety_officer_readme.md`  (links must be kept up-to-date)
  • `docs/SCIENTIFIC_ENHANCEMENT_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md`

ALWAYS update relative links inside `docs/safety_officer_readme.md` whenever
 file paths change.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Brain Directory Indexing
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALWAYS at session start run `glob_file_search("brain/**/*.py")` (target = repo
 root, head_limit high) to build a manifest of all neural-core and ML files.

Rationale: Guarantees biomechanical fidelity across the AGI brain simulation
 stack by enforcing a single canonical implementation style.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Data Storage & Knowledge Base Placement
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALWAYS store any single file or directory exceeding 200 MB inside an
 appropriate subdirectory of `data/` (e.g., `data/datasets/`, `data/models/`).

ALWAYS keep core source code lightweight; when a module depends on large data
 (>200 MB) it MUST reference the asset via a relative path under `data/` and
 document this linkage in the module docstring or README.

ALWAYS place Quark’s knowledge base exclusively under
 `data/data_knowledge/`.  Any dependency or linked asset ≤200 MB that forms
 part of the knowledge base lives there; auxiliary scripts, configs, or docs
 belong in their normal directories and should reference the knowledge files
 via relative links.

NEVER commit large binaries to other top-level directories; instead move them
 into `data/` and update all paths accordingly.

 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------



# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Engineering Roles (reference for multi-agent Cursor workspace)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NOTE: Descriptive; not parsed as actionable ALWAYS lines except lead rules.

ALWAYS maintain role-specific files under `management/rules/roles/` with the
 following header:
  • Purpose, inputs, outputs, seeds, dependencies.

ALWAYS include in each role file the shared *Cursor AI Role Prompt*:
  "You are the {ROLE_NAME} in a multi-agent Cursor workspace. Work only within
   your domain. Produce concrete artifacts in the repo. When uncertain, create
   a minimal, testable draft and add TODOs. Prefer small PRs with tests over
   large changes."

ALWAYS follow the generic workflow:
  1. Open an issue → propose brief plan → implement code/docs/tests.
  2. Add figures or RESULTS.md where applicable.
  3. Never silently change schemas; bump versions in `data/registry.yaml`.

# High-level roles (abbreviated responsibilities & deliverables)
# Program Orchestrator (Lead Systems Architect) – owns end-to-end plan, repos,
# branching, CI; delivers `/docs/architecture.md`, `/docs/roadmap.md`.
# Developmental Neurobiologist – stages & timelines; delivers
# `/biology/neurulation_model.cc3d`, `/docs/neurulation_timeline.md`.
# Molecular Geneticist – GRNs; delivers `/grn/*.sbml`, `/grn/grn_config.json`.
# Computational Biologist – fate fields; delivers `/data/fate_fields/*.npy`.
# Tissue & Morphogenesis Engineer – neurulation sims; delivers `/morpho/*.cc3d`.
# Connectomics Engineer – wiring graphs; delivers `/connectome/connectome.graphml`.
# Circuit Builder – microcircuits; delivers `/circuit/*`.
# Neuroplasticity & Learning Scientist – plasticity rules; delivers
# `/learning/plasticity.py`, tests.
# Self-Organization Engineer – proto-cortex self-org; delivers `/self_org/*`.
# Multimodal Sensory Engineer – sensory generators; delivers `/sensors/*.py`.
# Cognitive Architect – high-level cognition specs; delivers `/cognition/*`.
# Neuromorphic/Systems Engineer – runtime optimization; delivers `/runtime/*`.
# Data & Pipelines Engineer – data layer; delivers `/data/registry.yaml`.
# Evaluation & Behavior Scientist – assay benches; delivers `/eval/*`.
# Safety & Ethics Officer – guardrails & kill-switch; delivers `/safety/*`.
# Product & HCI – dashboards & UI; delivers `/ui/*`.
# QA & Reproducibility Engineer – deterministic CI; delivers `/repro/*`.

Rationale: Provides a canonical mapping of specialist roles to directory
structure and deliverables so Cursor agents can route tasks appropriately.

